                                               User Stories

                                             Admin & Analytics
                                           Actor : Admin/Manager

User Story 1: Manage Books

Front of the card:
As an Admin, I want to add, update, or remove books, so that the bookstore’s catalog always stays relevant and accurate.

Back of the card:
● Admin can upload book details (title, author, publisher, genre, price, cover image, description).
● Admin can edit existing book details.
● Admin can remove books from the catalog.
● Changes should be reflected instantly in the user-facing store.
● System validates data before saving (e.g., price must be numeric, cover image must be a valid format).


User Story 2: Manage Reviews

Front of the card:
As an Admin, I want to monitor and remove inappropriate reviews, so that the platform maintains quality and credibility.

Back of the card:
● Admin can view all user reviews.
● Admin can flag/remove reviews containing offensive or irrelevant content.
● Admin can restore mistakenly deleted reviews (soft delete).
● Admin can filter reviews by book, rating, or date.
● Notifications sent to users if their review is removed.


User Story 3: Manage Authors & Publishers

Front of the card:
As an Admin, I want to add and manage author and publisher information, so that books are accurately categorized and linked
to their creators.

Back of the card:
● Admin can add author details (name, bio, photo, nationality, genre).
● Admin can add publisher details (name, logo, description, location).
● Admin can edit/update author and publisher information.
● Books can be linked to the respective author and publisher.
● Admin can deactivate authors/publishers if no longer active.


User Story 4: Analytics & Trends

Front of the card:
As a Manager, I want to view analytics on current trends and user preferences, so that I can make data-driven business 
decisions.


Back of the card:
● System displays most purchased books, most viewed books, and top-rated books.
● Manager can see user demographics (age, location, genre preferences).
● Graphs/charts showing trends over time (weekly, monthly, yearly).
● AI-driven insights on upcoming popular genres.
● Data export option (CSV/PDF) for reports.



                                         Reading & Progress Tracking
                                              Actor: End User

User Story 1: Reading Books

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to open and read a book in the app so that I can enjoy the content directly within the platform.

Back of the card:
● From the catalogue, clicking a book opens the reader interface.
● The system loads the book content (text, EPUB/PDF) in a responsive reading view.
● User can navigate between chapters/pages using scroll or navigation controls.
● Book content is formatted for readability (font size, background theme options).
● Reading progress is automatically tracked as the user moves through the content.

User Story 2: Marking a Book as Read

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to mark a book as "Read" so that I can keep track of books I have completed.

Back of the card:
● A “Mark as Read” button/option must be visible on the book’s detail page and inside the reader.
● Clicking it updates the user’s library status in Firestore (users/{uid}/library).
● Once marked, the book appears in the “Books Read” section of the profile.
● The status can be updated again (e.g., changed back to “Reading” if needed).

User Story 3: Marking a Book to Read in the Future

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to add a book to my "To Read" list so that I can plan future reading.

Back of the card:
● A “Save to To-Read List” button must be visible on the book’s detail page.
● Clicking it saves the book’s ID to the user’s Firestore library with status to_read.
● The “To Read” list is accessible from the user profile/dashboard.
● The user can remove the book from the list or change its status anytime.

User Story 4: Viewing Books Read

Front of the card:
As a user, I want to view a list of all books I’ve read so that I can see my completed reading history.

Back of the card:
● The “Books Read” section is accessible from the user profile.
● It displays a list/grid of all books marked with status read.
● Each entry shows cover image, title, author, and date completed.
● The user can click any book to revisit its details or open it again.
● The system updates this list in real time when new books are marked as read.

User Story 5: Cross-Device Sync

Front of the card:
As a user, I want my reading progress, bookmarks, and highlights to sync across devices so that I can continue reading seamlessly.

Back of the card:
● The system stores progress/bookmarks/highlights in Firestore under users/{uid}.
● Progress is auto-synced every few seconds or on chapter change.
● When the user opens the same book on another device, the system loads the last saved progress automatically.
● If progress differs between devices, the system resolves by using the most recent update (updatedAt field).
● Bookmarks and notes are synced in real time, ensuring consistency across devices.




                                    Catalogue & Discovery 
                                      Actor: End User


User Story 1: Browse Catalogue by Genre

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to browse books by specific genres, so that I can discover new books when I'm in the mood for a certain type of story.

Back of the Card:
●A list of available genres is displayed on the 'Explore' page.
●Each genre in the list is clickable.
●Clicking a genre navigates to a new page that displays only books from that selected genre.
●The genre page has a title that clearly identifies the genre being viewed.


User Story 2: Basic Search

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to search for books by their title or an author's name, so that I can find exactly what I'm looking for without having to browse.

Back of the Card:
●A search bar is present and functional in the site header.
●Searching by a known book title returns that book in the results.
●Searching by a known author's name returns books by that author.
●A "No results found" message is shown for searches that have no matches.

User Story 3: View Trending Books

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to see a list of what's currently trending, so that I can stay up-to-date with popular books and see what others are enjoying.

Back of the Card:
●A section titled "Trending Now" is visible on the homepage.
●The section displays a collection of books.
●Clicking on any book within the section navigates to that book's detail page.

User Story 4: Find New Releases

Front of the Card:
As a reader, I want to easily find a dedicated section for 'New Releases,' so that I can keep up with the latest books as soon as they become available.

Back of the Card:
●A clickable link or section for "New Releases" is present on the homepage.
●The "New Releases" page displays books sorted with the newest publications first.
●Only books published within the last 30 days are included in this section.

User Story 5: Track Explored Books

Front of the Card:
As a curious reader, I want to see a personal statistic of how many books I've explored from the total catalogue, so that I can track my discovery journey on the platform.

Back of the Card:
●The user's profile page displays a counter showing "X out of Y books explored".
●The 'X' value increments by one after the user visits the detail page of a book for the first time.
●The counter does not increment when visiting a previously explored book's page again.
